    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>macro-influencer</strong> is a social media creator with 100,000 to 1,000,000 followers who is recognised for expertise in a specific niche. They sit between micro-influencers (10K-100K, high engagement) and mega-influencers or celebrities (1M+, maximum reach). Macro-influencers combine <strong>substantial reach with topic credibility</strong> — a fitness macro with 400K followers reaches more people than most micro-influencers while remaining far more affordable than a celebrity endorsement.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Follower range</div>
            <div class="tms-value">100K – 1M</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Avg engagement rate</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-5%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Instagram cost/post</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$1,000-$10,000</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most brands defaulted to celebrity partnerships for decades. The influencer tier structure changed the playbook — macro-influencers deliver near-celebrity reach at a fraction of the cost, with audience trust built on genuine niche expertise rather than general fame.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a macro-influencer?</h2>
        <p>The influencer tier system classifies creators by follower count, with each tier having characteristic engagement rates, audience relationship styles, and cost structures:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Nano:</strong> 1,000-10,000 followers — 7-10% engagement, hyper-local trust, very low cost</li>
          <li><strong>Micro:</strong> 10,000-100,000 followers — 5-8% engagement, niche community trust</li>
          <li><strong>Macro:</strong> 100,000-1,000,000 followers — 3-5% engagement, broader reach with retained niche authority</li>
          <li><strong>Mega/Celebrity:</strong> 1M+ followers — 1-3% engagement, maximum reach, celebrity-level cost</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The macro tier is distinct because creators at this level are typically known for a specific domain — beauty, fitness, B2B marketing, personal finance — rather than for general celebrity. A macro-influencer in skincare reaches fewer people than Kim Kardashian but reaches a far more qualified audience for a skincare brand.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why macro-influencers exist as a tier</div>
          <p>At 100K+ followers, creators reach a threshold where content production becomes professionalised — studio-quality video, consistent posting schedules, dedicated brand deal management. This makes them reliable partners for campaign planning in ways that nano and micro creators often aren't yet.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why macro-influencers matter for brands</h2>
        <p>Four characteristics make macro-influencers a distinct and often optimal choice:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Meaningful reach at scale.</strong> 100K-1M followers translates to tens of thousands of people seeing a single post — enough to move awareness metrics for mid-market brands without celebrity budget requirements.</li>
          <li><strong>Niche authority.</strong> Unlike celebrities who endorse anything, macro-influencers are known within their category. A tech review macro with 300K followers carries genuine credibility when recommending software tools.</li>
          <li><strong>Professional content quality.</strong> Creators at this tier typically produce polished video and photography. Brands can use macro-influencer content in paid media amplification without additional production cost.</li>
          <li><strong>Mid-market budget fit.</strong> At $1,000-$10,000 per Instagram post, macro deals are accessible to brands with five- to six-figure influencer budgets. Celebrity deals start at $100,000+ and often require exclusivity.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How macro-influencer campaigns work</h2>

        <h3>Finding the right creator</h3>
        <p>Platforms like Upfluence, CreatorIQ, and AspireIQ let brands search by niche, location, audience demographics, and engagement rates. Key filters:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Category match — does this creator's audience match our buyer persona?</li>
          <li>Engagement rate — is the 3-5% benchmark being met, or are followers bought?</li>
          <li>Audience overlap — what percentage of followers fall in our target market?</li>
          <li>Brand safety — what has this creator posted about competitors or sensitive topics?</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Partnership structures</h3>
        <p>Standard macro-influencer deal types:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sponsored post</strong> — paid placement, disclosed as #ad or #sponsored</li>
          <li><strong>Product review</strong> — creator receives product, provides honest review</li>
          <li><strong>Affiliate programme</strong> — creator earns commission on tracked sales via unique link or code</li>
          <li><strong>Brand ambassador</strong> — ongoing relationship, typically 3-12 months, with content calendar commitments</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Performance tracking</h3>
        <p>Metrics to track per campaign:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Engagement rate (likes + comments + shares / followers)</li>
          <li>Link clicks from bio or swipe-up</li>
          <li>Promo code redemptions</li>
          <li>Follower growth during campaign period</li>
          <li>Conversion rate from influencer traffic</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Macro-influencer cost benchmarks by platform</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Platform</th><th>Content type</th><th>Cost range</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
