              <tr><td><strong>Instagram</strong></td><td>Story (24hr)</td><td>$500-$3,000</td><td>Flash promotions, event awareness</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>YouTube</strong></td><td>Dedicated video</td><td>$2,000-$20,000</td><td>In-depth reviews, tutorials</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>YouTube</strong></td><td>Integrated mention</td><td>$1,000-$5,000</td><td>Brand awareness in relevant content</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>LinkedIn</strong></td><td>Article or post</td><td>$1,500-$8,000</td><td>B2B, SaaS, professional services</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>TikTok</strong></td><td>Short video</td><td>$800-$5,000</td><td>Gen Z products, viral-first campaigns</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real macro-influencer campaign examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Skincare brand — Instagram macro campaign</h3>
        <p>A beauty macro-influencer with 350,000 followers completed a 3-post campaign for a skincare brand. The campaign reached 280,000 people, generated 12,000 interactions, and drove 1,500 website visits. Total cost: $4,500. Cost per engaged user: $0.375.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS — LinkedIn macro series</h3>
        <p>A marketing-automation SaaS partnered with a LinkedIn macro-influencer (220K followers) for a 4-part educational series on automation strategy. Each post drove 500+ demo page visits from qualified marketing professionals — a lead quality that paid search struggled to match at equivalent cost.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Macro-influencer vs micro-influencer — which to use</h2>
        <p>Neither is universally better. The right choice depends on campaign objective and budget.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use macro-influencers when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Awareness is the primary objective</li>
              <li>You need professional content for paid amplification</li>
              <li>Campaign requires few partnerships to manage</li>
              <li>Brand needs credibility transfer from a known voice</li>
              <li>Mid-to-large budget available ($5K-$50K per campaign)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use micro-influencers when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Conversion and trust are primary objectives</li>
              <li>Budget is limited but reach can be distributed</li>
              <li>Multiple niche communities need targeting</li>
              <li>Authentic peer recommendation tone matters</li>
              <li>Testing creative with lower per-unit cost</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for macro-influencer campaigns</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Audit engagement before contracting.</strong> A 500K-follower account with 0.8% engagement likely has bought followers. Use tools like HypeAuditor or manually check comment-to-like ratios.</li>
          <li><strong>Align on audience demographics, not just size.</strong> 300K followers in the wrong age bracket or geography delivers worse ROI than 80K followers in the exact right segment.</li>
          <li><strong>Brief clearly but allow creative control.</strong> Macro-influencers built their audience with a specific voice. Overly scripted content underperforms because followers detect inauthenticity.</li>
          <li><strong>Secure usage rights upfront.</strong> Negotiate rights to repurpose creator content in paid social and display ads. This eliminates production costs and often outperforms brand-produced creative.</li>
          <li><strong>Include FTC-compliant disclosure requirements in the contract.</strong> Posts must clearly disclose the paid relationship. Non-compliant posts risk brand and creator FTC penalties.</li>
          <li><strong>Track affiliate links and promo codes separately from organic traffic.</strong> Attribution is the hardest part of influencer measurement. Unique UTM parameters and creator-specific codes are the minimum tracking setup.</li>
          <li><strong>Plan for 2-4 posts, not 1.</strong> Single-post campaigns rarely achieve the repetition needed to move purchase intent. Series formats (3-4 pieces) consistently outperform one-offs.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — follower count without engagement audit</div>
          <p>A 500K-follower account sounds impressive. A 500K-follower account with 0.6% engagement and comments that look like "Great post!" spam is worthless. Always check engagement rate, comment quality, and follower growth charts for artificial spikes before signing a contract. Buying followers is common at this tier.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common macro-influencer mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Choosing reach over relevance</strong> — a fitness macro cannot effectively sell B2B software regardless of follower count.</li>
          <li><strong>Single-post campaigns</strong> — one post rarely moves purchase intent. Minimum 3 posts over 4-6 weeks for measurable effect.</li>
          <li><strong>No unique tracking links</strong> — without attribution, you can't prove ROI or compare macro vs micro performance.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-scripting content</strong> — heavily branded language kills the authenticity that makes macro-influencers valuable.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative comment patterns</strong> — check recent posts for recurring negative sentiment about the creator. You inherit that reputation.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
